[1]
Date: Tue, 13 Sep 2005 10:28:16 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: NewKerala.com, India, 13 Sep 2005 [edited]
<http://www.newkerala.com/newsdaily.php?action=fullnews&id=22261>

Even as the Union Health Ministry officials predicted that the menace of
Japanese Encephalitis (JE) will continue till December 2005, as many as 21
more deaths were reported during the last 24 hours, taking the toll in
Uttar Pradesh to 713.
Baba Raghav Das Medical College (BRDMC) in Gorakhpur, hub of the JE menace
in Eastern Uttar Pradesh, King George Medical University (KGMU) Hospital in
Lucknow, and other district hospitals are still receiving patients on a
regular basis.
As many as 25 districts in the state have been affected by the deadly
virus, and Allahabad has been newly added to the list of sensitive
districts. Of the fresh casualties reported, 7 deaths occurred at Allahabad
during the last 24 hours, a report said.
Meanwhile, a report quoting Union Health Ministry officials said that the
JE menace could continue till December 2005. More than 3000 patients have
so far been registered in the state since 28 Jul 2005, when the first case
was reported.
The eastern part of the state has been the worst affected with more than
2600 JE patients registered at BRDMC alone, official sources said here.
Patients from Maharajganj, Basti, Kushinagar, Ghazipur, Mau, Azamgarh, Sant
Kabirnagar, Deoria, Balrampur and Gonda have been admitted at the Gorakhpur
Medical College, sources added.
