[2]
Date: Tue, 13 Sep 2005 10:28:16 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sify, India, 13 Sep 2005 [edited]
<http://sify.com/news/fullstory.php?id=13939416>

The death toll from an outbreak of Japanese encephalitis in northern India
rose to 675 Tuesday after 11 more victims were reported but health
authorities said the illness was under control.
"At least 11 more persons died overnight, taking the toll to 675," said OP
Singh, health department chief in Uttar Pradesh.
Singh said 60 cases were admitted to hospitals overnight but the number of
arrivals had started to slow.
"The outbreak is under control and the influx of patients to hospitals has
come down," Singh said. "Fogging of insecticide in affected areas has
started. People have been advised to sleep under mosquito nets."
Doctors, however, said many children were being brought to the hospital
when they were already extremely unwell, making it hard to save them.
"People are still coming to hospitals with unconscious children in their
arms. Some of them are coming to us very late," said KP Kushwaha, of the
paediatrics department in BRD Medical College Gorakhpur.
Doctors have said they are struggling to treat the children in deplorable
medical conditions. They say there is a severe lack of life-saving
medicines, oxygen and medical staff and that a number of children are lying
2 to a bed.
Health workers say a lack of preventive action, such as widespread
vaccination, is to blame for the scale of the outbreak. The illness is
endemic to the region.
A court in Allahabad city, 200 kilometers (135 miles) southeast of the
state capital Lucknow, ordered the state and federal governments Tuesday to
supply anti-encephalitis vaccines in disease-ravaged areas. It also told
the governments to submit a progress report within 2 weeks on measures
taken to check the disease.
The court order followed a petition filed by a schoolteacher whose son died
of encephalitis in August 2005.
The disease, which is transmitted from pigs to humans via mosquitoes,
strikes during the annual monsoon rains from June to September.
Japanese encephalitis first surfaced in Uttar Pradesh in 1978, killing 721.
In 1980, 496 died from the disease and deaths reached a record 1228 in
1988. More than 4000 people have died in the state since the disease first hit.
In the neighboring Himalayan kingdom of Nepal, meanwhile, state media said
at least 204 people had died of encephalitis since it surfaced in mid-June
2005.
