Date: Wed, 14 Sep 2005
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: World Health Organization [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don>

Japanese Encephalitis (JE) in India - 13 Sep 2005
1145 cases of Japanese encephalitis have been reported from 14 districts of
Uttar Pradesh Province, India from 29 Jul to 30 Aug 2005. About 1/4 of
these (n=296) have died. 90 cases from the adjoining districts of Bihar
have also been admitted to the hospitals in Uttar Pradesh.
The majority of the affected villages have reported only single cases.
Entomological surveys in the affected villages have revealed high density
of _Culex tritaeniorhynchus_ and _Culex vishnui_ group -- the vectors of
Japanese Encephalitis (JE).
For more information, please see the web site of the WHO Regional Office
for South-East Asia
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The crucial vectors (the Culex mosquitoes) that carry JEV and transmit to
humans were surveyed. We would like to know if further data corroborating
the entomological surveys are available. Entomologists are invited to share
their opinions with us regarding how and why the JE epidemic in the Uttar
Pradesh area has progressed so far this year. - Mod.RY]
[Elsevier reference:
